# Image segmentation using Python with container

The application allows you to perform image segmentation using the Qualcomm Neural Processing SDK with Python bindings, all from within a docker container.

## Prerequisites[](https://docs.qualcomm.com/bundle/publicresource/topics/80-70018-50/image-segmentation-using-python.html?vproduct=1601111740013072&version=1.4&facet=Qualcomm%20Intelligent%20Multimedia%20SDK#prerequisites "Click to copy section url")

Ensure that the following are available:

*   Ensure that you are using a Linux host computer with a docker installed.
*   Download the required model files on the device. For instructions, see [Download model and label files](https://docs.qualcomm.com/bundle/publicresource/topics/80-70018-50/download-model-and-label-files.html?vproduct=1601111740013072&version=1.4&facet=Qualcomm%20Intelligent%20Multimedia%20SDK).

Figure : Workflow to set up host container ![](data:image/png;base64,)

To set up the host container, do the following:

1.  Install [Qualcomm® Package Manager (QPM3)](https://qpm.qualcomm.com/#/main/tools/details/QPM3).
2.  Download and extract Qualcomm Neural Processing SDK:
    
    ```css
    qpm-cli --login <username>
    ```
    
3.  Download scripts and model attachments to run the sample mode.
    1.  Download the Dockerfile and scripts and prepare the directory for storing the image.
        
        ```cpp
        git clone https://git.codelinaro.org/clo/le/sdk-tools.git -b imsdk-tools.lnx.1.0
        ```
        
        ```powershell
        cd sdk-tools/snpe-container-python
        ```
        
        ```undefined
        mkdir images
        ```
        
        The snpe-container-python file has the Dockerfile and scripts. Run all the commands from this directory.
        
    2.  Copy the test image in a new folder called inputs and rename the test image as input\_image.jpg.
        
        ```undefined
        mkdir inputs
        ```
        
        ```css
        cp <path of test image> ./inputs
        ```
        
        ```powershell
        cd inputs
        ```
        
        ```powershell
        mv <test_image_name> input_image.jpg
        ```
        
    3.  Set up the host device for cross compilation:
        
        ```undefined
        sudo groupadd docker
        ```
        
        ```powershell
        sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
        ```
        
        ```undefined
        newgrp docker
        ```
        
        Until the host device is rebooted, continue running these commands for every new console that's used to run the docker.
        
        ```cpp
        sudo apt-get install qemu-user-static qemu-system-arm
        ```
        
        ```css
        docker run --rm --privileged multiarch/qemu-user-static --reset -p yes
        ```
        
        ```powershell
        docker buildx rm builder
        ```
        
        ```css
        docker buildx create --name builder --driver docker-container --use
        ```
        
        ```css
        docker buildx inspect --bootstrap
        ```
        
    4.  Build the docker image. Populate the `<path-to-sdk-tools>/targets/config.json` file.
        
        The following code shows an updated sample config.json file.
        
        The following inputs are mandatory:
        
        *   `SNPE_version`
        *   `Base_Image`
        *   `Target_platform`: The following are field values for each SoC:
            *   For QCS6490–`qcm6490`
            *   For QCS8275–`qcs8300`
            *   For QCS9075–`qcs9100`
        *   `URL` (ensure that the address provided isn't the same as your current directory)
        
        Note To prevent code failures, ensure that you remove the comments before using it.
        
        ```java
        {
            "SNPE_version":"v2.32.0.250228",
            "Base_Image": "ubuntu:22.04",
            "Target_platform": "qcm6490",
        
            "Additional_tag_container": "",
            "Additional_tag_image": "",
            "URL": "<path-to-sdk-tools>/snpe-container-python/images",
        
            "DeviceID" : null
        }
        ```
        
4.  Build the docker image:
    
    ```undefined
    sudo apt install jq
    ```
    
    ```css
    cd  <path to sdk-tools>/snpe-container-python
    ```
    
    ```css
    source scripts/host/docker_env_setup.sh
    ```
    
    ```css
    qml-docker-build-image targets/config.json
    ```
    
    Save the docker image:
    
    ```css
    qml-docker-device-save-image targets/config.json
    ```
    
    The docker image is compressed and the TAR file is saved at the directory specified in the `URL` field in config.json.
    
    *   If Additional\_tag\_image is empty, the compressed image is stored as qml.tar.
    *   If Additional\_tag\_image is populated, the compressed image is stored as qml-\<field value\>.tar.
5.  Push the docker image on the device:
    
    ```xml
    scp <path specified in URL field>/qml.tar root@<IP address of target device>:/opt
    ```
    
6.  Start the container:
    
    ```xml
    ssh root@<ip of target>
    ```
    
    ```powershell
    mount -o remount, rw /usr
    ```
    
    ```undefined
    systemctl restart docker
    ```
    
    ```typescript
    docker load < /opt/qml.tar
    ```
    
7.  Run the docker image on the device:
    
    ```typescript
    docker run -it -d --device=/dev/fastrpc-cdsp-secure \
    --device /dev/kgsl-3d0 --device /dev/dma_heap/system --device /dev/dma_heap/qcom,system \
    -v /usr/lib/libCB.so:/usr/lib/libCB.so \
    -v /usr/lib/libOpenCL.so:/usr/lib/libOpenCL.so \
    -v /usr/lib/libOpenCL_adreno.so:/usr/lib/libOpenCL_adreno.so \
    -v /usr/lib/libbase.so.0:/usr/lib/libbase.so.0 \
    -v /usr/lib/libcdsprpc.so:/usr/lib/libcdsprpc.so \
    -v /usr/lib/libcutils.so.0:/usr/lib/libcutils.so.0 \
    -v /usr/lib/libdmabufheap.so.0:/usr/lib/libdmabufheap.so.0 \
    -v /usr/lib/libglib-2.0.so.0:/usr/lib/libglib-2.0.so.0 \
    -v /usr/lib/libgsl.so:/usr/lib/libgsl.so \
    -v /usr/lib/libgthread-2.0.so.0:/usr/lib/libgthread-2.0.so.0 \
    -v /usr/lib/libion.so.0:/usr/lib/libion.so.0 \
    -v /usr/lib/libllvm-qcom.so:/usr/lib/libllvm-qcom.so \
    -v /usr/lib/liblog.so.0:/usr/lib/liblog.so.0 \
    -v /usr/lib/libpcre.so.1:/usr/lib/libpcre.so.1 \
    -v /usr/lib/libsync.so.0:/usr/lib/libsync.so.0 \
    -v /usr/lib/libvmmem.so.0:/usr/lib/libvmmem.so.0 \
    -v /usr/lib/libatomic.so.1:/usr/lib/libatomic.so.1 \
    -h qml --name qml qml
    ```
    
    A docker image called qml should be running. To check this image, run the following command:
    
    ```powershell
    docker ps
    ```
    
8.  Push input\_image.jpg to the device.
    
    ```css
    scp <path to inputs_directory>/input_image.jpg root@<IP address of target device>:/opt/ 
    ```
    
    ```xml
    ssh root@<ip of target>
    ```
    
    ```typescript
    docker cp /opt/input_image.jpg qml:/opt/
    ```
    
9.  Copy the deeplab\_resnet50.dlc model to the docker:
    
    ```typescript
    docker cp /etc/models/deeplabv3_resnet50.dlc qml:/opt/
    ```
    

## Run the application[](https://docs.qualcomm.com/bundle/publicresource/topics/80-70018-50/image-segmentation-using-python.html?vproduct=1601111740013072&version=1.4&facet=Qualcomm%20Intelligent%20Multimedia%20SDK#run-the-application "Click to copy section url")

1.  Run the Qualcomm Neural Processing SDK model using Python bindings:
    
    ```css
    docker exec qml python3 /mnt/qml/src/python/snpe/test_snpe/snpe_segmentation_app.py -d /opt/deeplabv3_resnet50.dlc -i /opt/input_image.jpg -r dsp -o /mnt/qml/output/ -b USERBUFFER_FLOAT -p /usr/lib/libSNPE.so
    ```
    
    *   The output image is saved in the container at /opt/.
    *   The output from the DLC model (RAW file) is saved at /mnt/qml/output/.
2.  Copy the output from the container to the device:
    
    ```typescript
    docker cp qml:/opt/output.jpg /opt/
    ```
    
3.  To pull the image from the device to host, run the command on your host computer:
    
    ```typescript
    scp root@<IP address of target device>:/opt/output.jpg ./
    ```
